e=Manila's 'Combo Tita' ends Youtuber's 'Tawag' reign|first=ABS-CBN|last=News}}</ref>\n|Sam Mangubat\n|- style=\"background:#f0f8ff;\"\n|My Love<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/entertainment/11/25/16/cover-artist-keeps-tawag-win-streak-alive|title=Cover artist keeps 'Tawag' win streak alive|first=ABS-CBN|last=News}}</ref>\n|Sam Mangubat\n|- \n|Unbreakable<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pressreader.com/malaysia/the-borneo-post/20160329/282892319788437|title=PressReader.com \u2013 Connecting People Through News|website=pressreader.com}}</ref>\n|[[Luhan]] of [[Exo (band)|EXO]]\n|- style=\"background:#f0f8ff;\"\n|What I Want is What I've Got\n|Northside\n|- \n|If I Let You Go\n|Northside\n|-style=\"background:#f0f8ff;\"\n|Swear It Again\n|Northside\n|- \n|My Love\n|Northside\n|- style=\"background:#f0f8ff;\"\n|Open Your Heart\n|Northside\n|-\n|I Need You\n|Northside\n|- style=\"background:#f0f8ff;\"\n|Flying Without Wings\n|Northside\n|-\n|I Don't Wanna Fight\n|Northside\n|-\n|If I Let You Go<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymotion.com/video/x61mm2z|title=Can Mark McKeown impress with his Westlife cover- \u2013 Auditions Week 3 \u2013 The X Factor 2017 \u2013 Video Dailymotion|date=23 September 2017|website=Dailymotion}}</ref>\n|Mark McKeown\n|- style=\"background:#f0f8ff;\"\n|Us Against the World\n|The Brooks\n|-\n|My Love\n|[[Lunafly]]\n|- style=\"background:#f0f8ff;\"\n|If I Let You Go\n|Crimson Ensemble\n|-\n|If I Let You Go\n|Priceless\n|- style=\"background:#f0f8ff;\"\n|If I Let You Go\n|Penelope Matanguihan\n|-\n|Fool Again\n|Penelope Matanguihan\n|- style=\"background:#f0f8ff;\"\n|Unbreakable\n|[[Julienne Taylor]]\n|-\n|Fool Again\n|Angelo Villegas\n|- style=\"background:#f0f8ff;\"\n|Flying Without Wings\n|[[Nicholas McDonald]]\n|-\n|Evergreen\n|Daniel Russell\n|-\n|Flying Without Wings\n|[[Jonathan Pierce]]\n|}\n\nSource: [[Discogs]]\n{{col-end}}\n\nDespite their popularity, some artist have expressed their dislike to the group like [[Eminem]], [[Christina Aguilera]], [[Bob Geldof]], [[Pierce Brosnan]], [[Liam Gallagher]], [[Melanie C]], [[Victoria Beckham]], [[Gary Barlow]], [[Damon Albarn]] and [[Noel Gallagher]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rapdirt.com/eminem-slams-westlife-after-woopin-them-in-the-charts/1283/|title=Eminem Slams Westlife After Woopin' Them in the Charts |website=rapdirt.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcarchives.com/index.asp?id=2415&PageNo=&keywords=&date=&f=2|title=Christina Aguilera snubs Westlife \u2013 The Mariah Carey Archives|website=mcarchives.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/westlife-im-with-the-brand-551646.html|title=Westlife: I'm with the brand|date=31 May 2004}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.femalefirst.co.uk/music/musicnews/Westlife-1527.html|title=Westlife Attack Pierce Brosnan|website=Femalefirst.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=http://content.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,2048094,00.html|title=Go West, Young Men|first=Jeff|last=Chu|date=7 May 2001|journal=Time}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/the-spice-girls-30-1310741 |title=IT'S ALL TOO MUCH FOR POSH |work=NME |date=19 October 2000}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/melanie-c-3-1308509 |title=MEL GIVES WESTLIFE HELL! |work=NME |date=19 October 2000}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2006/nov/24/4 |title=Westlife's magic lost on Barlow |work=The Guardian |date=19 October 2006 |accessdate=12 November 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.contactmusic.net/liam-gallagher/news/liam-lashes-out-at-westlife-hunk |title=Liam lashes out at Westlife hunk |publisher=Contact Music |date=19 October 2013 |accessdate=14 November 2013}}</ref> Some have also criticized the band for having lots of covers, having the same sound on every albums released, lack of use of musical instruments and lack of songwriting skills. Feehily revealed in 2009: \"There were many songs which I would be even scared to mention, you know, that were suggested to us which we turned down. There were many cover versions and many original songs that were either terrible. There was loads of stuff through the years, like '[[You Are Not Alone]]' by [[Michael Jackson]]?, that were suggested by their record company chief Cowell\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.skiddle.com/news/all/Westlife-wanted-for-Jackson-song/4543/ |title=Westlife wanted for Jackson song |work=Skiddle |date=30 November 2009}}</ref> Westlife have proven to have more original songs, worked with many songwriters and music producers and co-written numerous songs throughout their career. (See [[Westlife songlist]] for the compilation.) Band members can also play at least one musical instrument and Egan can play up to five musical instruments and a grade eight pianist.\n\n==Collaboration==\nBefore their success, the band served as supporting opening acts for the boy bands Backstreet Boys and Boyzone. Since then, the group has recorded studio and live performances with music acts including Mariah Carey (\"Against All Odds (Take a Look at Me Now)\"), [[Lulu (singer)|Lulu]] (\"[[Back at One (song)|Back at One]]\"), Joanne Hindley (\"The Way You Look Tonight\"), [[Diana Ross]] (\"When You Tell Me That You Love Me\"), [[Donna Summer]] (\"[[No More Tears (Enough Is Enough)]]\"), and [[Delta Goodrem]] (\"[[All Out of Love]]\"), \"[[If I Had Words]]\" with The Vard Sisters, \"I Have A Dream\" with [[Indonesia]]n child-star [[Sherina Munaf|Sherina]]. These songs were also recorded and included on various albums. In 2002, Westlife re-recorded their hit song \"Flying Without Wings\" with [[Mexico|Mexican]] singer [[Cristian Castro]] and with Korean singer [[BoA]] as two separate duets.\n\nWestlife has performed live duets with many other music artists including: [[Will Smith]], [[Wyclef Jean]], [[Toby Keith]], [[Esperanza Spalding]], [[Luis Fonsi]], [[Alexander Rybak]], [[Amadou and Mariam]], [[Willow Smith]], [[Jaden Smith]], [[Jada Pinkett Smith]], [[Lang Lang]], [[Wang Leehom]] (\"You Raise Me Up\"),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.massitsallhere.com/2016/11/29/boston-chinese-pop-star-connects-east-west-culture/|title=In Boston, Chinese Pop Star Connects East and West Culture \u2013 Massachusetts It's All Here|date=29 November 2016}}</ref> [[Mary Black]] (\"Walking in the Air\"), [[Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor]] (\"[[Silent Night]]\"), Dean Verbeeck (\"Swear It Again\"), [[Donny Osmond]] (\"[[Crazy Horses]]\"), [[Kevin Spacey]] (\"[[Beyond the Sea (song)|Beyond the Sea]]\" and \"Fly Me to the Moon\"), Mariah Carey (\"[[Never Too Far/Hero Medley]]\"), [[Secret Garden (duo)|Secret Garden]] (\"You Raise Me Up\"),<ref name=\"auto\"/> Lionel Richie ([[Easy (The Commodores song)|\"Easy\"]]), Boyzone (\"[[No Matter What (Boyzone song)|No Matter What]]\"), Ronan Keating ([[The Dance (Garth Brooks song)|\"The Dance\"]]), Ray Quinn (\"[[That's Life (song)|That's Life]]\"), [[JLS]] (\"Flying Without Wings\"), [[Dolores O'Riordan]] of [[The Cranberries]] (\"[[Little Drummer Boy]]\") and recorded with various artists for a charity single and performed for a live concert or television performances specials with music artists such as [[Steps (group)|Steps]], [[Lisa Scott-Lee]], [[5ive]], [[S Club 7]], [[The Cheeky Girls]], [[Tony Hadley]], [[Blazin' Squad]], Gareth Gates, [[Liberty X]], [[Girls Aloud]], Busted, [[McFly]], [[Jonathan Wilkes]], [[Suranne Jones]], [[Darius Campbell|Darius]], [[Emma Bunton]], [[Leona Lewis]], Rod Stewart, [[Cheryl (singer)|Cheryl]], [[Mika (singer)|Mika]], [[Michael Bubl\u00e9]], [[Joe McElderry]], [[Miley Cyrus]], [[James Blunt]], [[Blue (English band)|Blue]], Gary Barlow, [[Mark Owen]], [[Jon Bon Jovi]], [[James Morrison (singer)|James Morrison]], Alexandra Burke, [[Jason Orange]], [[Susan Boyle]], [[Rachel Stevens]], JLS, [[Jamie Cullum]], [[Gloria Estefan]], [[Kylie Minogue]], Robbie Williams, and [[V (band)|V]], where the former boyfriend of Feehily was a member named [[Kevin McDaid]].\n\n==Artistry and influences==\nWestlife is mainly a pop, pop/rock, club/dance, dance-pop, contemporary pop/rock, teen pop male group.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/westlife-mn0000201983|title=Westlife &#124; Biography, Albums, Streaming Links|website=AllMusic}}</ref> They cited [[Michael Jackson]] and [[Backstreet Boys]] as their musical influences.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://h2g2.com/entry/A87767329|title=h2g2 - Westlife - Irish Boy Band|first=Not Panicking|last=Ltd|website=h2g2.com}}</ref>\n\n==Products and endorsements==\nSome of the products that Westlife officially released, aside from their music releases, include video games, [[Cadbury]] chocolates, books, calendars, and tour merchandises such as T-shirts, jewellery, stationary, toiletries, dolls, watches, clocks, mugs, duvets, wallpaper, key chains, and posters. Their second studio album ''Coast to Coast'' received additional products mostly in Asia that include [[Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore)|MRT]] transport ticket, picture card calendar, postcard set, signed fold-out poster, glossy slipcase and [[Filofax]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eil.com/shop/moreinfo.asp?catalogid=172078 |title=Westlife \u2013 ''Coast to Coast'' + poster & postcards Korea CD ALBUM (172078) |publisher=Eil.com |date=29 November 2000 |accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://eil.com/shop/moreinfo.asp?catalogid=171142 |title=Westlife \u2013 ''Coast to Coast'' + poster & cards Taiwan CD ALBUM (171142) |publisher=Eil.com |date=20 November 2000 |accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref> They also received sponsorship from [[Tayto (Republic of Ireland)|Tayto]] in 2000<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/pop-go-the-sponsors-1.253283|title=Pop go the sponsors|website=The Irish Times}}</ref> and for their concert tours from [[Calvin Klein]] in 2001, [[Adidas]] in 2002 and [[Volkswagen]] in 2011. They have official and unofficial books released. One of them is the book written by the members of Westlife was released on 16 June 2008 by [[Harper Collins|HarperCollins UK]] Publishing entitled, '[[Westlife - Our Story]]', as part of their 10th year celebration.<ref>{{cite book |title=Westlife \u2013 Our Story |publisher=Amazon UK |isbn=978-0007288120 |year=2008 }}</ref> The band released two perfume gift sets, \"[[X (fragrance)|X]]\" and \"[[With Love (Westlife fragrance)|With Love]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.factorme.co.uk/fragrance/westlife-perfume-3-piece-gift-set-edp-p-296.html |title=Westlife Perfume 3 piece perfume Gift Set |publisher=FactorMe.co.uk |accessdate=13 October 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111127000829/http://www.factorme.co.uk/fragrance/westlife-perfume-3-piece-gift-set-edp-p-296.html |archivedate=27 November 2011  }}</ref>\n\n==Charitable support==\nThe group has supported various charitable causes. They were involved in the \"Helping For Haiti\" charity single that was released in February 2010. As well as releasing a cover version of \"Uptown Girl\" for [[Comic Relief]], one of their biggest selling singles to date.\n\nThey have participated in a [[Royal British Legion]] poppy appeal, Irish Blood for Life 2004 and did an advertisement for [[Galway]]'s [[Irish Water Safety]] campaign.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/488183.stm |title=WestLife aid poppy appeal |work=BBC News|date=30 October 1999 |accessdate=13 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.galwayindependent.com/making-waves/making-waves/westlife-support-iws/ |title=Westlife support IWS |work=Galway Independent |date=16 April 2008 |accessdate=13 October 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081008043846/http://www.galwayindependent.com/making-waves/making-waves/westlife-support-iws/ |archivedate=8 October 2008 |df= }}</ref> They also lent their support to the [[Irish Blood Transfusion Service]] (IBTS).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.giveblood.ie/About_Us/Newsroom/Press_Releases/2004/1_in_4_will_need_a_blood_transfusion_-_Westlife_lends_support_as_IBTS_launches_Blood_for_Life_Week_19-25th_September_2004.html |title=1 in 4 will need a blood transfusion \u2013 Westlife lends support as IBTS launches Blood for Life Week 19\u201325 September 2004 |publisher=Giveblood.ie |date=25 September 2004 |accessdate=13 October 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111004045222/http://www.giveblood.ie/About_Us/Newsroom/Press_Releases/2004/1_in_4_will_need_a_blood_transfusion_-_Westlife_lends_support_as_IBTS_launches_Blood_for_Life_Week_19-25th_September_2004.html |archive-date=4 October 2011 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> On 4 November 2005, they performed with other music artists at [[Coca-Cola Dome]] in [[Johannesburg]], South Africa for The \"Unite of the Stars\" Gala Banquet charity concert that supports four charities: the [[Nelson Mandela Children's Fund]], Unite Against Hunger, St. Mary's Hospital and the Topsy Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/Entertainment/SouthAfrica/Celebs-jet-into-SA-20061031|title=Celebs jet into SA|date=November 2006}}</ref> They also performed live for charity on [[Sport Relief]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CeXVNhk3ROY|title=Westlife \u2013 Us Against The World (Sport Relief 2008) HQ|last=pommivabrik|date=21 December 2009|via=YouTube}}</ref> [[Macmillan Cancer Support]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.macmillan.org.uk/aboutus/news/newsroom.aspx?NewsListing_List_GoToPage=32|title=Media centre|date=1 January 1900}}</ref> Cro\u00ed, Western [[Alzheimer's]], O\u2019Dwyer [[Cheshire]] Home, [[County Mayo|Mayo]] Cancer Support Group, [[Marie Keating Foundation]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.castlebar.ie/TF_Shows/Westlife_Charity_Weekend_832_printer.shtml|title=Castlebar \u2013 County Mayo \u2013 Westlife Charity Weekend|website=castlebar.ie}}</ref> Outward Bound Trust,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://london.eventful.com/events/exclusive-event-westlife-aid-outward-bound-trust-/E0-001-034874193-2|title=Exclusive event with Westlife in aid of The Outward Bound Trust|website=Eventful}}</ref> [[ChildLine]], [[Children in Need]], [[Sheffield]]'s Children Hospital. They had also helped for auctions on [[Meningitis]] Research Foundation,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.meningitis.org/news-media/charity-auction-%E2%80%93-vip-21939|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120903181632/http://www.meningitis.org/news-media/charity-auction-%E2%80%93-vip-21939|url-status=dead|title=Charity auction \u2013 VIP Westlife tickets|date=3 September 2012|archivedate=3 September 2012}}</ref> Carlton Celebrity Auction for Centrepoint (for the homeless),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.compleatseanbean.com/celebrityauction.html|title=Carlton Celebrity Auction|website=compleatseanbean.com}}</ref> the [[National Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Children]], and [[The Samaritans]]),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/regionals/sligochampion/news/westlife-launch-samaritans-new-sligo-text-service-27524946.html|title=Westlife launch Samaritans' new Sligo text service|website=Independent.ie}}</ref> Zutto charity painting, Pushing The Envelope (for [[National Literacy Trust]]). They've visited also Great Ormond Street Hospital.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailystar.co.uk/news/latest-news/168340/Westlife-lead-stars-supporting-Christmas-appeal-at-Great-Ormond-Street|title=Westlife lead stars supporting Christmas appeal at Great Ormond Street|date=20 December 2010}}</ref> They've been involved also with the following organizations: [[Royal National Institute for the Deaf]] (RNID),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.co.uk/whats-on/out-and-about/jade-13-gets-to-meet-her-westlife-heroes-thanks-to-the-star-1-321407|title=Jade, 13, gets to meet her Westlife heroes ... thanks to The Star|website=thestar.co.uk}}</ref> [[Cancer Research UK]], [[United Nations]]' [[World Food Programme]] (WFP),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.un.org/en/story/2010/01/326182-actor-will-smith-and-family-auction-art-help-un-feed-hungry-haiti|title=Actor Will Smith and family auction art to help UN feed hungry in Haiti|date=8 January 2010}}</ref> Muscle Help Foundation,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ablemagazine.co.uk/muscle-help-foundation-big-lottery-fund/|title=Muscle Help Foundation Awarded \u00a310,000 By Big Lottery Fund|website=ablemagazine.co.uk|date=28 August 2014}}</ref> Global Breast Cancer Awareness Campaign<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thefreelibrary.com/Shire+Health+International:+First+Ever+Global+Breast+Cancer+Awareness...-a0122725633|title=Shire Health International: First Ever Global Breast Cancer Awareness Campaign Unites Independent Charities from around the World. \u2013 Free Online Library|website=thefreelibrary.com}}</ref> and Real Man campaign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cosmopolitan.com/uk/reports/a12985/hot-celebs-show-theyre-real-men/|title=Hot celebs show they're 'Real Men'|date=8 August 2011}}</ref> They are also included as ambassadors of The [[Irish Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Children]] (ISPCC). As part of IPSCC, Feehily signed up for their anti-bullying campaign, \"Join the Fight for Children's Rights\".<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.rte.ie/entertainment/2012/0423/436941-westlife/|title=Feehily launches anti-bullying week|journal=RT\u00c9 News|date=23 April 2012}}</ref> and Aware,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://foot.ie/threads/148460-Mark-Feehily-and-Sligo-Rovers-support-Aware|title=Mark Feehily and Sligo Rovers support Aware|website=foot.ie}}</ref> Byrne for Heart attack and Asthma awareness campaigns, [[Daily Star (United Kingdom)|Daily Star]]'s Reclaim Our Streets crusade,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/get-your-mits-on-westlife-kit-1-2062336|title=GET YOUR MITS ON WESTLIFE KIT!|website=yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk}}</ref> Byrne for [[Oxfam]]'s [[East Africa]] famine appeal (by [[Celtic F.C.]] v [[Manchester United F.C.]] football match),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celticfc.net/news/1392?item=1392|title=Charity the winner as Paradise rocks to Larsson's treble|first=Mark|last=Henderson}}</ref> and for Children's Hospice [[South West England|South West]] (by [[Truro]] charity football match).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.falmouthpacket.co.uk/sport/4533728.Bryan_Robson_and_Paul_Merson_to_play_in_charity_match_at_Truro/|title=Bryan Robson and Paul Merson to play in charity match at Truro|website=Falmouth Packet}}</ref> Filan, Byrne for [[Soccer Aid]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/entertainment/celebrity/westlife-stars-shane-filan-and-nicky-1059957|title=Westlife stars Shane Filan and Nicky Byrne enjoy training session with Celtic|first=Beverley|last=Lyons|date=25 May 2010}}</ref> [[J.P. McManus]] Invitational Pro-Am, One World Beat.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/jp-mcmanus-hosts-lavish-starstudded-sendoff-for-ap-mccoy-31439148.html|title=JP McManus hosts lavish star-studded send-off for AP McCoy|work=The Belfast Telegraph}}</ref> Filan for [[Irish Red Cross]] (by [[Sligo Rovers F.C.]] Showgrounds football match),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sligotoday.ie/printable.php?id=5087 |title=Westlife's Shane will line out against Sligo Rovers |publisher=Sligo Today |access-date=19 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180219151606/http://www.sligotoday.ie/printable.php?id=5087 |archive-date=19 February 2018 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> and Egan for [[Strandhill]] Indonesian Relief Fund (SIRF, in aid of the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami|South Asian tsunami]] victims).\n\n==Members==\n;Current \n* [[Nicky Byrne]] <small>(1998\u20132012, 2018\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Kian Egan]] <small>(1998\u20132012, 2018\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Markus Feehily|Mark Feehily]]  <small>(1998\u20132012, 2018\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Shane Filan]] <small>(1998\u20132012, 2018\u2013present)</small>\n\n;Former \n* [[Brian McFadden]] <small>(1998\u20132004)</small>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Westlife discography|Westlife songs}}\n* ''[[Westlife (album)|Westlife]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Coast to Coast (Westlife album)|Coast to Coast]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[World of Our Own]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Turnaround (Westlife album)|Turnaround]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[...Allow Us to Be Frank]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Face to Face (Westlife album)|Face to Face]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[The Love Album (Westlife album)|The Love Album]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Back Home (Westlife album)|Back Home]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Where We Are]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Gravity (Westlife album)|Gravity]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Spectrum (Westlife album)|Spectrum]]'' (2019)\n\n==Selected videography==\n{{Main|Westlife videography|List of Westlife appearances}}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by Westlife}}\n\n==Tours==\n{{Main|Westlife tours}}\n\n===Concert tours===\n'''Headlining'''\n*East Meets Westlife Tour\n*[[Where Dreams Come True Tour]]\n*[[World of Our Own Tour]]\n*[[Unbreakable Tour (Westlife concert tour)|Unbreakable Tour]] as The Greatest Hits Tour\n*[[Turnaround Tour]]\n*[[Number Ones Tour (Westlife concert tour)|Number Ones Tour]]\n*[[Face to Face Tour]]\n*[[The Love Tour]]\n*[[Back Home Tour]] / 10th anniversary\n*[[Where We Are Tour (Westlife)|Where We Are Tour]]\n*[[Gravity Tour]]\n*[[Greatest Hits Tour (Westlife)|The Greatest Hits Tour]] / The Farewell Tour\n*[[The Twenty Tour]]\n*[[Stadiums in the Summer Tour]]\n\n'''Supporting'''\n*[[Backstreet Boys]] \u2013 [[Backstreet's Back Tour]]\n*[[Boyzone]] \u2013 Where We Belong Tour\n\n===Promotional tours===\n*1998\u20132012; 2018\u2013present UK and Ireland Tour\n*1999 European, East Asian and Southeast Asian Tour\n*2000 European, North American, South American and Asian Tour<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/779656.stm |title=Exhausted Bryan rejoins Westlife |publisher=BBC |date= |accessdate=2018-11-07}}</ref>\n*2001, 2002 European, Korean, Mexican and United States Tour\n*2003 European, Hong Kong, Japan, and Malaysian Tour\n*2005, 2006 European, Taiwan Tour\n*2007 Australian Tour\n*2009 Swedish Tour<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.westlife.com/global/news/global/2009/11/26/westlife_in_sweden |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110810075204/http://www.westlife.com/global/news/global/2009/11/26/westlife_in_sweden |url-status=dead |archive-date=2011-08-10 |title=Westlife in Sweden |publisher=westlife.com |date= |accessdate=2018-11-07}}</ref>\n*2019 Singapore, Indonesian, Chinese, Swedish Tour<ref name=\"Twitter\"/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikipedia books|Westlife}}\n*[[Boy band#Best-selling boy bands|List of best-selling boy bands]]\n*[[UK Singles Chart records and statistics]]\n* [[List of artists who reached number one on the UK Singles Chart]]\n* [[List of best-selling music artists in the United Kingdom in singles sales]]\n*[[List of artists by number of UK Singles Chart number ones]]\n*[[List of UK Singles Chart number ones of the 2000s]]\n*[[List of UK Singles Downloads Chart number ones of the 2000s]]\n*[[List of UK Albums Chart number ones of the 2000s]]\n* [[List of artists who reached number one in Ireland]]\n* [[List of songs that reached number one on the Irish Singles Chart]]\n*[[List of best-selling albums in the Philippines]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website|http://westlife.com}}\n\n{{Westlife}}\n{{Westlife songs}}\n{{Shane Filan}}\n{{Brian McFadden}}\n{{MTV EMA for Best UK & Ireland Act}}\n{{Portal bar|Music|1990s|Europe|Ireland}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Westlife| ]]\n[[Category:Brit Award winners]]\n[[Category:Irish boy bands]]\n[[Category:Irish pop music groups]]\n[[Category:1998 establishments in Ireland]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1998]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 2012]]\n[[Category:Musical groups reestablished in 2018]]\n[[Category:2012 disestablishments in Ireland]]\n[[Category:2018 establishments in Ireland]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Dublin (city)]]\n[[Category:Ballad music groups]]\n[[Category:Teen pop groups]]\n[[Category:RCA Records artists]]\n[[Category:Sony BMG artists]]\n[[Category:Syco Music artists]]\n[[Category:Universal Music Group artists]]\n[[Category:Vocal quartets]]\n[[Category:Vocal quintets]]\n[[Category:World Music Awards winners]]\n[[Category:EMI Records artists]]\n[[Category:MTV EMA winners]]\n", "name_user": "Jellysandwich0", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Westlife"}
{"title_page": "Neil Barofsky", "text_new": "'''Neil M. Barofsky''' (born 1970), a partner in the Litigation Department of national [[law firm]] Jenner & Block LLP, focuses his practice on [[white collar crime|white collar]] investigations, complex commercial [[litigation]], monitorships and examinerships.  Immediately before joining Jenner & Block, Mr. Barofsky was Senior Fellow at [[New York University School of Law]]\u2019s Center on the Administration of Criminal Law, an adjunct professor at the law school and affiliated with the Mitchell Jacobson Leadership Program on Law and Business.<ref>[https://its.law.nyu.edu/facultyprofiles/profile.cfm?personID=35257 Profile]</ref>  He was SIGTARP, the Special [[United States Treasury Department]] [[Inspector General]] overseeing the [[Troubled Assets Relief Program]] (TARP), from late 2008 until his resignation at the end of March 2011, previous to which he was Assistant [[United States Attorney]] for the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of New York|Southern District of New York]] from 2000 to 2008.\n\n==Education==\nBarofsky went to [[Spanish River High School]] in [[Boca Raton]], Florida<ref>https://blogs.law.nyu.edu/magazine/2010/neil-barofsky-95-profile/</ref> and completed his undergraduate studies at the [[University of Pennsylvania]], earning a bachelor's degree in economics from [[Wharton School of Business]]. He graduated with honors from [[New York University School of Law]] in 1995.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bush picks New York prosecutor Neil Barofsky to oversee $700B bailout|first=Kerry|last=Burke|first2=Corky|last2=Siemaszko|date=November 15, 2008|newspaper=[[New York Daily News]]|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/money/2008/11/14/2008-11-14_bush_picks_new_york_prosecutor_neil_baro.html|accessdate=January 27, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Troubled Asset Relief Program and Special Inspector Generalship==\n{{expand section|date=January 2010}}\nBarofsky was nominated for the job of [[Oversight of the Troubled Assets Relief Program|overseeing the TARP]] by President [[George W. Bush]] on November 14, 2008<ref>{{cite news|title=Bailout Lacks Oversight Despite Billions Pledged|first=Amit R.|last=Paley|date=November 13, 2008|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/11/12/AR2008111202846.html|accessdate= January 27, 2010}}</ref> and was confirmed by the [[United States Senate]] on December 8, 2008, after confirmation was delayed by Senator [[Jim Bunning]].<ref>{{cite news|title=TARP cop ratchets up restrictions on rescue cash |first=Neil|last=Roland|newspaper=Financial Week|url=http://www.financialweek.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=2009901079973|accessdate=January 27, 2010}}</ref>\n\nUntil he was confirmed, the role was handled internally by the Treasury Department's inspector general, [[Eric Thorson]], who had expressed concerns about the difficulty of properly overseeing the complex program in addition to his regular responsibilities.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bush names bailout overseer|date=November 15, 2008|agency=[[Associated Press]] | work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |url=http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-barofsky15-2008nov15,0,2690416.story|accessdate=January 27, 2010}}</ref>\n\nAs Inspector General, Barofsky, \"[a] life-long [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] who donated money to the [[Barack Obama 2008 presidential campaign|Obama campaign]],\"<ref name=Greenwald/> was viewed as \"one of the most impressive and courageous political officials in Washington\"<ref name=Greenwald>[[Glenn Greenwald|Greenwald, Glenn]] (2011-02-15) [https://www.salon.com/2011/02/15/anonymity_9/ Standard Washington cowardice], ''[[Salon.com]]''</ref> for his willingness to \"stand up to some of the most powerful people and institutions in Washington or on Wall Street.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=An Investigator Presses to Uncover Bailout Abuse|first=Mary Williams|last=Walsh|date=January 25, 2010|accessdate=January 27, 2010|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/26/business/26tarp.html|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> He \"vigilantly fought for his independence as TARP watchdog and has been relentless in his criticism of Treasury officials and especially [[Timothy Geithner|Tim Geithner]].\"<ref name=Greenwald/> The TARP program money was used to invest in, and in some cases rescue, a number of banks, the automakers GM and Chrysler, the insurance company [[American International Group|AIG]] as well as a number of real estate companies.  The role of the chief watchdog of the government\u2019s $700 billion TARP program was to root out and prosecute waste, fraud and abuse. Under Barofsky, the office published 9 quarterly results and 13 audits.<ref name=\"dc.citybizlist.com\">http://dc.citybizlist.com/5/2011/2/14/TARP-Inspector-General-Neil-Barofsky-Sends-Resignation-Letter-to-President-Obama.aspx</ref><ref name=DB01/>\n\nOn February 14, 2011 Barofsky sent a letter to President Obama stating that he would resign his post on March 30, 2011, to spend more time with his family. At the time of his resignation, his office had more than 140 investigations underway.<ref name=DB01>{{cite news| url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2011/02/14/bailout-inspector-barofsky-resign/ | work=The New York Times | first=Ben | last=Protess | title=Barofsky Stepping Down as Watchdog of TARP | date=February 14, 2011}}</ref>  By then, his office charged a few dozen people with civil or criminal fraud, resulting in 14 convictions, more than $550 million in fraud losses avoided, and $150 million in fraudulent earnings recovered for taxpayers.<ref name=\"dc.citybizlist.com\"/><ref>https://www.scribd.com/doc/48808729/Resignation-Letter-of-TARP-Special-Inspector-General</ref>\n\n\"[O]ne Treasury official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, was quoted as saying '[H]e's been consistently wrong about a lot of big things.\"<ref>Dennis, Brady, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2011/02/14/AR2011021406089.html Neil Barofsky, TARP's outspoken overseer, will resign\"], ''Washington Post'', February 14, 2011 8:30 PM ET. Retrieved 2011-02-18.</ref> Commentator [[Glenn Greenwald]] noted the unnamed official had made the assertion about Barofsky \"without identifying a single alleged error,\" and attacked the \"utter cowardice and lack of professionalism needed to produce this passage\" on the part of both the newspaper and the official.<ref name=\"Greenwald\" />\nBarofsky currently works as a tax compliance watchdog at Credit Suisse [https://www.wsj.com/articles/credit-suisse-monitor-neil-barofsky-does-job-with-gusto-1430384275] [https://insideparadeplatz.ch/2017/01/19/schwarzgeld-jaeger-zulauf-verlaesst-cs-ueber-nacht/]\n\n==Books==\n* ''Bailout: An Inside Account of How Washington Abandoned Main Street While Rescuing Wall Street'' (2012). {{ISBN|9781451684933}} {{OCLC|793575355}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.sigtarp.gov/|title=The Office of the Special Inspector General for the Troubled Asset Relief Program}}\n* {{C-SPAN|Neil Barofsky}}\n** [http://www.c-span.org/video/?307720-1/qa-neil-barofsky C-SPAN ''Q&A'' interview with Barofsky, September 23, 2012]\n* [http://www.economicpolicyjournal.com/2012/09/talking-war-on-drugs-tarp-and-power_2.html Robert Wenzel interviews Barofsky, September 2, 2012]\n* {{cite web |last=Roberts |first=Russ |title=Barofsky on Bailouts |url=http://www.econtalk.org/archives/_featuring/neil_barofsky/ |work=[[EconTalk]] |publisher=[[Library of Economics and Liberty]] |authorlink=Russ Roberts |date=September 3, 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barofsky, Neil}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Troubled Asset Relief Program]]\n[[Category:Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania alumni]]\n[[Category:New York University School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:People associated with Jenner & Block]]\n", "text_old": "'''Neil M. Barofsky''' (born 1970), a partner in the Litigation Department of national [[law firm]] Jenner & Block LLP, focuses his practice on [[white collar crime|white collar]] investigations, complex commercial [[litigation]], monitorships and examinerships.  Immediately before joining Jenner & Block, Mr. Barofsky was Senior Fellow at [[New York University School of Law]]\u2019s Center on the Administration of Criminal Law, an adjunct professor at the law school and affiliated with the Mitchell Jacobson Leadership Program on Law and Business.<ref>[https://its.law.nyu.edu/facultyprofiles/profile.cfm?personID=35257 Profile]</ref>  He was SIGTARP, the Special [[United States Treasury Department]] [[Inspector General]] overseeing the [[Troubled Assets Relief Program]] (TARP), from late 2008 until his resignation at the end of March 2011, previous to which he was Assistant [[United States Attorney]] for the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of New York|Southern District of New York]] from 2000 to 2008.\n\n==Education==\nBarofsky went to [[Spanish River High School]] in [[Boca Raton]], Florida<ref>https://blogs.law.nyu.edu/magazine/2010/neil-barofsky-95-profile/</ref> and completed his undergraduate studies at the [[University of Pennsylvania]], earning a bachelor's degree in economics from [[Wharton School of Business]]. He graduated with honors from [[New York University School of Law]] in 1995.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bush picks New York prosecutor Neil Barofsky to oversee $700B bailout|first=Kerry|last=Burke|first2=Corky|last2=Siemaszko|date=November 15, 2008|newspaper=[[New York Daily News]]|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/money/2008/11/14/2008-11-14_bush_picks_new_york_prosecutor_neil_baro.html|accessdate=January 27, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Troubled Asset Relief Program and Special Inspector Generalship==\n{{expand section|date=January 2010}}\nBarofsky, \"[a] life-long [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] who donated money to the [[Barack Obama 2008 presidential campaign|Obama campaign]],\"<ref name=Greenwald/> was nominated for the job of [[Oversight of the Troubled Assets Relief Program|overseeing the TARP]] by President [[George W. Bush]] on November 14, 2008<ref>{{cite news|title=Bailout Lacks Oversight Despite Billions Pledged|first=Amit R.|last=Paley|date=November 13, 2008|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/11/12/AR2008111202846.html|accessdate= January 27, 2010}}</ref> and was confirmed by the [[United States Senate]] on December 8, 2008, after confirmation was delayed by Senator [[Jim Bunning]].<ref>{{cite news|title=TARP cop ratchets up restrictions on rescue cash |first=Neil|last=Roland|newspaper=Financial Week|url=http://www.financialweek.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=2009901079973|accessdate=January 27, 2010}}</ref>\n\nUntil he was confirmed, the role was handled internally by the Treasury Department's inspector general, [[Eric Thorson]], who had expressed concerns about the difficulty of properly overseeing the complex program in addition to his regular responsibilities.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bush names bailout overseer|date=November 15, 2008|agency=[[Associated Press]] | work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |url=http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-barofsky15-2008nov15,0,2690416.story|accessdate=January 27, 2010}}</ref>\n\nAs Inspector General, Barofsky was viewed as \"one of the most impressive and courageous political officials in Washington\"<ref name=Greenwald>[[Glenn Greenwald|Greenwald, Glenn]] (2011-02-15) [http://www.salon.com/news/opinion/glenn_greenwald/2011/02/15/anonymity/index.html Standard Washington cowardice], ''[[Salon.com]]''</ref> for his willingness to \"stand up to some of the most powerful people and institutions in Washington or on Wall Street.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=An Investigator Presses to Uncover Bailout Abuse|first=Mary Williams|last=Walsh|date=January 25, 2010|accessdate=January 27, 2010|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/26/business/26tarp.html|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> He \"vigilantly fought for his independence as TARP watchdog and has been relentless in his criticism of Treasury officials and especially [[Timothy Geithner|Tim Geithner]].\"<ref name=Greenwald/> The TARP program money was used to invest in, and in some cases rescue, a number of banks, the automakers GM and Chrysler, the insurance company [[American International Group|AIG]] as well as a number of real estate companies.  The role of the chief watchdog of the government\u2019s $700 billion TARP program was to root out and prosecute waste, fraud and abuse. Under Barofsky, the office published 9 quarterly results and 13 audits.<ref name=\"dc.citybizlist.com\">http://dc.citybizlist.com/5/2011/2/14/TARP-Inspector-General-Neil-Barofsky-Sends-Resignation-Letter-to-President-Obama.aspx</ref><ref name=DB01/>\n\nOn February 14, 2011 Barofsky sent a letter to President Obama stating that he would resign his post on March 30, 2011, to spend more time with his family. At the time of his resignation, his office had more than 140 investigations underway.<ref name=DB01>{{cite news| url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2011/02/14/bailout-inspector-barofsky-resign/ | work=The New York Times | first=Ben | last=Protess | title=Barofsky Stepping Down as Watchdog of TARP | date=February 14, 2011}}</ref>  By then, his office charged a few dozen people with civil or criminal fraud, resulting in 14 convictions, more than $550 million in fraud losses avoided, and $150 million in fraudulent earnings recovered for taxpayers.<ref name=\"dc.citybizlist.com\"/><ref>https://www.scribd.com/doc/48808729/Resignation-Letter-of-TARP-Special-Inspector-General</ref>\n\n\"[O]ne Treasury official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, was quoted as saying '[H]e's been consistently wrong about a lot of big things.\"<ref>Dennis, Brady, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2011/02/14/AR2011021406089.html Neil Barofsky, TARP's outspoken overseer, will resign\"], ''Washington Post'', February 14, 2011 8:30 PM ET. Retrieved 2011-02-18.</ref> Commentator [[Glenn Greenwald]] noted the unnamed official had made the assertion about Barofsky \"without identifying a single alleged error,\" and attacked the \"utter cowardice and lack of professionalism needed to produce this passage\" on the part of both the newspaper and the official.<ref name=\"Greenwald\" />\nBarofsky currently works as a tax compliance watchdog at Credit Suisse [https://www.wsj.com/articles/credit-suisse-monitor-neil-barofsky-does-job-with-gusto-1430384275] [https://insideparadeplatz.ch/2017/01/19/schwarzgeld-jaeger-zulauf-verlaesst-cs-ueber-nacht/]\n\n==Books==\n* ''Bailout: An Inside Account of How Washington Abandoned Main Street While Rescuing Wall Street'' (2012). {{ISBN|9781451684933}} {{OCLC|793575355}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.sigtarp.gov/|title=The Office of the Special Inspector General for the Troubled Asset Relief Program}}\n* {{C-SPAN|Neil Barofsky}}\n** [http://www.c-span.org/video/?307720-1/qa-neil-barofsky C-SPAN ''Q&A'' interview with Barofsky, September 23, 2012]\n* [http://www.economicpolicyjournal.com/2012/09/talking-war-on-drugs-tarp-and-power_2.html Robert Wenzel interviews Barofsky, September 2, 2012]\n* {{cite web |last=Roberts |first=Russ |title=Barofsky on Bailouts |url=http://www.econtalk.org/archives/_featuring/neil_barofsky/ |work=[[EconTalk]] |publisher=[[Library of Economics and Liberty]] |authorlink=Russ Roberts |date=September 3, 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barofsky, Neil}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Troubled Asset Relief Program]]\n[[Category:Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania alumni]]\n[[Category:New York University School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:People associated with Jenner & Block]]\n", "name_user": "WikiReviewer6", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTroubled Asset Relief Program and Special Inspector Generalship:Corrected source link; moved similar material from the same source together.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neil_Barofsky"}
